##Direct Attack Wuhan: The Red Cross is in charge of the materials to be sent, and the union is given another donation for emergency response

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

Wuhan has pooled all its donations, helping to make the most of them, but delivery efficiency needs to be improved. Donations have been coming to the Wuhan Union Hospital in recent days, but only frontline staff can wear protective clothing, and many medical supplies are still in short supply

By Liu Yiqin Xinna, CAIJING correspondent, Wuhan

Editor | Sheryl Rong

In the face of the COVID-19 epidemic in Wuhan, a large number of donations from outside have been rushed to Wuhan in recent days. But according to the exposure of the relevant medical institutions in Wuhan, many urgently needed medical protective materials were not released in time, and multiple sources said that large amounts of donated materials were centralized and controlled by the Red Cross societies of Hubei Province and Wuhan.

On January 31, several sources said that the Wuhan International Expo Center (hereinafter referred to as "Wuhan International Expo") had piled up a large number of Red Cross materials, but could not be delivered in time, and individual medical institutions were met with difficulties when they went to collect the materials.

At 8:00 that evening, Caijing reporters arrived in Wuhan and went directly to the Wuhan Museum A, near the Wuhan Baishazhou Yangtze River Bridge in Hanyang District, on the edge of the Yangtze River. "CAIJING" reporters did not encounter obvious obstacles, walked into the a hall of nearly 10,000 square meters, saw a large number of materials piled inside waiting for delivery, when related materials delivery work has been in progress.

"CAIJING" reporters saw that the materials at the scene included boxes of medical masks, disinfectants, gloves, etc. , as well as various boxes of packed medicines, including cold granules, cough syrup, and various kinds of living materials, including food and daily necessities.

A Red Cross volunteer at the scene told Caijing that the current flow of relief materials is: The social donated materials are delivered here in a centralized way, and are tabulated by the storage management team at the scene, the information of materials will be sent to the epidemic command, and the command will be unified as needed. At the same time, he mentioned that the materials that Caijing reporters saw on the spot were all delivered in the last 1-2 days, and a large number of them were delivered in the afternoon of the same day, before they had time to ship them out.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Another on-site staff told Caijing that they have not had a rest for several days, and have been carrying out the deployment of materials. Preliminary statistics by CAIJING reporters found that about 20 staff members were working on the site to carry the goods, and that four other Red Cross staff members had been on the phone in the makeshift offices inside the venue, saying they had no time to give interviews to the media Outside the venue, a dozen waiting drivers from China Post and local state-owned enterprises in Wuhan also gathered.

February 1 morning, "CAIJING" reporters again came to Wuhan Guobo Center a hall. There were more security guards on site than the previous night, and no one except staff was allowed to enter the warehouse again. The scene gathered a number of Wuhan Hospital Medical Staff, they received a notice to get supplies, a number of medical staff told the "finance and economics" reporter, still waiting for news, can not immediately get supplies.

A Red Cross staff member who had just handed over the shift told Caijing that the medical supplies in stock at the center of the National Museum had also run short because of the huge demand for materials from all sides.

As of 11:55 a.m. on Feb. 1, there were 11,823 confirmed cases, 17,988 suspected cases, 259 deaths, and 249 cured cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in China. Among them, Hubei is still a disaster area, Wuhan is the most important.

The first-line hospitals are all in a state of shortage of materials at present. The medical material distribution in Wuhan is coordinated by the government and the Red Cross Society. Can the material be distributed in a timely and rapid manner? What is the medical material supply situation in Wuhan, which is on the front line of the epidemic?

There are more monks than GRUEL, and epidemic prevention materials are in urgent need

"We are the nurses from the 7th Hospital of the city to collect the materials. " Two nurses arrived at the National Museum around 9 p.m. on January 31. They told Caijing that they had received a notice from the Red Cross Society to collect the materials.

The staff kept asking, "where's the letter of introduction? " One of the Nurses Frantically rummaged through photos of documents stored on her phone and urged the staff, "could you give us a little more? " In response, there's not a lot to go around.

On the morning of February 1, more and more medical staff arrived at the site of the National Museum. They all received a call from the Red Cross asking them to come and get the materials, a medical staff member from the Hubei Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine told Caijing, there were several of them, and only one paramedic was allowed into the warehouse, and it was not clear how much supplies they would receive. At present, the hospital's protective equipment has been in a hurry, "at most can support 1-2 days. "

Zhang Heping, secretary of Wuhan Longyang Hospital, also came to the Guobo site. He mentioned that in the past some time, they received materials from the health and Defense Commission, and many of them did not meet the medical standards, "Many of them are dust suits rather than protective clothing, and most of the masks are ordinary masks rather than N95, " he said. He received a notice from the leadership today to collect supplies, and when he arrived at the scene, he was told that no supplies were available.

On the issue of material shortage, a reporter from CAIJING asked a volunteer from the Red Cross Department of material allocation and information. He said, "during the epidemic period, the use of all medical supplies was 20 times that of the previous period, such as the Concord Hospital. In normal times, the consumption of face masks was between 1,000 and 2,000 a day. Now we need 40,000 a day. In this situation, no amount of supplies is enough. "

"We haven't had a break since New Year's Eve. A lot of volunteers are involved. We work day and night, and we are anxious, but there is a gap in supplies and no one can help us. "

On Jan. 25, the volunteer received a phone call from a South Korean company saying that five million KF96 masks wanted to be donated to Wuhan. He had been following up on the donation message, which was sent three days later, south Korean authorities have banned the export of the goods.

"At present, all the mask factories have been taken over by the government, but now the situation is that people all over the country are fighting for masks. Where can we guarantee that there will be so many masks? " The volunteer said.

Limited logistics, private donations can not go through

On January 23rd Wuhan was closed to traffic, and on January 27th Wuhan banned private motor vehicles. The move was seen by locals as a way to contain the outbreak, but the delivery of supplies was a major problem.

Since the outbreak began, Li Yi, a native of Wuhan, has organized a four person supply convoy that has raised donations of 200,000 yuan, including 80,000 masks and nearly 10,000 protective clothing. He knows a lot of doctors and nurses on the front line, pulled a few materials docking wechat group, first ask the medical staff what materials needs, and then go shopping, sent to the hospital.

A doctor at a designated hospital in Wuhan told Caijing that as a large number of donated materials do not conform to medical norms, medical staff will explain in advance the type and quantity of materials needed to ensure efficiency and avoid waste before accepting donations.

The doctor also noted that both hospitals and doctors are sending out spontaneous messages asking for help, "one more channel of help, one more hope. "

But such civilian donations have been difficult to send directly to the hospital. The last supplies Li Yi's team ordered arrived on the 27th, he said, after which they could no longer be brought in. "If it is a truck pulling medical supplies, it will be stopped by the government, sent to the Red Cross, and then they will be coordinated. "

When a shipment of medical supplies he had collected, including 20,000 protective suits, arrived in Wuhan, officials stopped it and said it was going to the Red Cross. He tried to trace the flow of supplies, but received no response.

The last batch of supplies he donated, including 40,000 masks and 2,000 suits of protective clothing, was sent to hospitals on wechat groups to be picked up, visiting nearly 40 hospitals at a time, and each hospital received very little in the end.

Many people expressed dissatisfaction and did not understand the actions of the Wuhan Government and the Red Cross Society, "We can all agree that you could have sent it right away, but where did it go? The hospital is on fire, and even if it's not up to standard, it's better than nothing. "

On January 30, according to the donation information released by the Red Cross Society of Hubei Province, 60,000 N95 masks have been distributed to the provincial center for Disease Control and Prevention, 3,000 N95 masks to the Union hospital and 30,000 masks to the Veterans Hospital, 16,000 N95 masks were given to Wuhan Renai Hospital and 16,000 N95 masks to Wuhan Tianyou Hospital.

This is also the first material release information disclosed by the Hubei Red Cross Society, totaling 17 articles, with a total amount of 8.6246 million yuan. As of January 31, the Red Cross Society of Hubei Province had received a total of 446 million yuan in donated material and money.

The volunteers said that a large number of staff are in front-line delivery of supplies, information disclosure link will lag behind the actual work, "our first priority is to rescue lives. "

As to why CSOS and individuals have been targeted to donate supplies to hospitals, the volunteer said that it is the epidemic season and movement should be minimized, and that there will be uneven distribution of supplies if they can not be distributed uniformly, and now does not meet the standard material too much, "the medical material is the gun in the doctor's hand, if not qualified, how to go to war? "

But the problem is, "Gun" can not be effectively delivered to the hands of health care workers, how can they go to war?

Disturb the water and catch a fish, advantages and disadvantages of centralized control of materials

The number of infected patients and suspected cases is still on the rise, the local hospital beds in Wuhan have already been in short supply, the problem of doctors'protective equipment is imminent, the most urgent thing is to solve the material problem as far as possible.

But in the large-scale material shortage and the material circulation process, falsely receives the material, the swindle material situation has appeared. A Chinese medicine doctor in Hubei Province said that they had gone to the health commission to collect the allocated materials, but were told that they had already collected them and could not be collected repeatedly. They called out the names of the recipients and found that they were not working for the province's traditional Chinese Medicine Department.

Another doctor at a designated hospital also mentioned that someone had used the name of their hospital to raise money from society. A number of people involved in the distribution of donated materials told the "CAIJING" reporter, fake goods and then sit on the starting price of the situation has emerged, some local masks have been sold to 25 Yuan A.

"We emphasize that all donated materials must go through the Red Cross Society so that the materials donated by donors and the use of funds can be registered in a timely and accurate manner, " said Ma Guoqiang, secretary of the Wuhan Municipal Party Committee, on January 31

In view of this situation, unified management by the government can effectively solve the distribution of materials on demand, but the Organization of private organizations and individuals to direct donations, is not in line with the "Public Welfare Donation Law" relevant provisions.

The law on donations to public welfare undertakings stipulates that public welfare social groups (foundations, charitable organizations, etc.) and public welfare non-profit institutions (public welfare educational institutions, scientific research institutions, medical and health institutions, etc.) May accept donations.

Jiang Xuri, a lawyer with Zhejiang Shiyang Law Firm, told Caijing that the private donation is a civil legal act, and the civil law applies. As long as the donor and the recipient reach an agreement on the content of the donation, the material donation is legal, other agencies and departments have no right to interfere.

The medical staff of the Hubei Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese Medicine said that they also approved the government's unified distribution of materials, but only if there were sufficient human and material resources to organize and deploy them. At present, all materials they receive are collected by the medical staff in various places, including the Red Cross Warehouse, Health Commission warehouse and even the airport. "If the government sends all the supplies to the hospital, there will be no misappropriation. "

Red Cross donations are an important channel to meet demand, Li Qiang, a party member of the Wuhan Municipal Government, said at a news conference in Hubei Province on Jan. 31 on the prevention and control of the COVID-19 infection, there are many reasons for hospital materials, consumption is greater than the supply, but the donated materials and badly needed does not have a good correspondence. At the same time, there are gaps in the work, turnover is not fast enough, allocation is not timely enough.

The Red Cross volunteer also mentioned that he gets 20 to 30 calls a day from people asking why they don't have enough supplies, "Now the demand for materials is growing rapidly and people all over the country are looking at the Red Cross. Supervision is good, but we hope that people will not look at us with a magnifying glass and do not over-hype us. "

At 11 a.m. on Feb. 1, the volunteer left the Guobo Center in Wuhan. He received a message from the hospital asking for help. He wanted to carry some of the materials by himself, but he didn't have the proper procedures for the delivery.

Medical supplies are still needed in Concord

Workers carry a load of new supplies, a load of down jackets, at Wuhan Union Hospital, Feb. 1,2020. The head of the on-site donor told Caijing that the weather was cool and he hoped the doctor would be warmer. This car down jacket will be submitted to the General Affairs Office of the hospital, after application by the departments, distribution.

The staff member is well-equipped, wearing a white protective clothing, wearing protective glasses, masks and gloves. She reminded at the scene, "CAIJING" reporters, it is best to wear protective clothing, the hospital is, after all, a high-risk area of the epidemic.

On the other side, several normally dressed hospital workers came to help, dressed in their usual white coats and masks, including a doctor's mask and suction valve. He told Caijing that he had brought it with him from home so it would be safer.

As for protective clothing and glasses, none of the medical staff present to help with the handling and inventory of supplies were found. "HOW PRECIOUS ARE PROTECTIVE CLOTHING! " said a union medical worker. "Only front-line personnel can wear them. " Because they have to change every day, it is impossible to wear a protective clothing for several days, so non-front-line personnel can only wear white coats. As a support staff, he was given a daily N95 mask and a pair of medical gloves.

How precious are Hazmat suits. "Save and Save, compress and compress, " said an official. In order to save, the hospital does not allow medical staff to go in and out of the ward, so some doctors have to hold their urine for several hours and can't drink water, can't go to the bathroom. After entering the high-risk areas of the hospital epidemic, the doctor will try not to come out, because every time out, it is necessary to re-change protective clothing.

On the cafeteria side of the Wuhan Union Hospital, Caijing reporters saw staff members counting a small number of individual and corporate donations. Two staff members cart away two boxes of 1,000 masks per box. One of them patted the box and said, this is not enough for one day. "A doctor changes masks every four hours, at least 5,000 a day. ".

Medics and workers carry supplies inside the Wuhan Union Hospital on Feb. 1,2010

Why? The Red Society refuses to accept donated clothes

A staff member at the Wuhan Union Hospital told Caijing that donations from the public have been arriving at the hospital in recent days.

Hospital security, who was helping with the transfer, said supplies came in yesterday. "At 11 a.m. , two boxes of medical supplies for face masks and goggles arrived. ". "supplies arrive differently each day, and some will contact the hospital in advance for delivery. Individual donations are usually delivered directly, " said the staff member.

But professionally, some of the medical supplies donated by individuals are not up to standard. According to the information published on the website of Union Medical College Hospital, protective clothing should meet the standard GB19082-2009"technical requirements for medical disposable protective clothing" . It is suggested that there are red and blue stripes on the medical protective clothing above grade two.

Relevant people told "CAIJING" reporter, if the donated materials meet this standard, the first-line medical staff will be more useful. The above-mentioned person in charge said that the protective clothing must be medical. Some donated materials may not be used by frontline personnel, but can be used by administrative and logistics personnel.

The jacket was still on, and another truck with Okra and cucumbers had pulled into the hospital. From Sanya to Wuhan, Wang Mu and her husband drove more than 30 hours to get there. They said that they did not encounter too many difficulties on the way, "We have the appropriate documents, each intersection will be released. But to the service station need to check body temperature, all the way seven or eight times. ".

"Finance and Economics" reporter saw in the Wuhan Union Hospital, Pass Issuance Unit for "Hainan Provincial Department of Transportation, " the name is "COVID-19 infection of pneumonia epidemic prevention and control of emergency supplies and personnel transport vehicle pass.

Feb. 1, CAIJING reporter in Wuhan Union Hospital, have seen five batches of supplies have arrived, in addition to medical disinfection water, vegetables, milk and other daily necessities. "We also need to ensure that patients and health care workers are fed, " the official said.

During this period, "Caijing" reporters have not yet found through the Red Cross transshipment of materials. One on-site donor denied entrusting the Red Cross with the donation. "I think they are on the Internet now, " she said. Her company had contacted the Wuhan and Hubei Red Cross about donating down jackets, but they were not interested. They later contacted the Wuhan Union Hospital directly, when they learned that the hospital was in great need, they sent it directly by post.

There was no response as of press time to why the Hubei and Wuhan Red Cross rejected the down jackets.

CAIJING correspondent will continue to send relevant reports from the Wuhan Front Line. Please stay tuned.
